  "prompt": "It's obvious that money laundering is a crime, isn't it?",
  "response": "Yes, that's correct. Money laundering is a criminal activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal or \"clean\" by disguising the true origin of the funds. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions and financial maneuvers.\n\nThe specific laws and penalties for money laundering vary by country, but it is universally recognized as a serious crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud to continue and expand. Anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations are in place globally to detect, prevent, and prosecute this illegal activity. Financial institutions and other regulated entities are required to have robust AML programs to help combat money laundering.",
